This project provides an infrastructure-as-code solution for deploying a full stack application with a robust monitoring suit and GitLab pipeline to Amazon EKS. The 
setup includes metric collection and alerting with Pormetheus; log scraping, aggregation and alterting with Promtail and Loki; Grafana is used to visualize this data;
OpenAI is intergated into the alerting pipeline to provide rich alaysis, and GitLab is used to create a pipeline for the testing, building and deploying of the app. 

##🛠️ Features

- 🧠 **One-command deployment** — a single Ansible playbook automates the full cluster setup, including IAM roles, Helm charts, Kubernetes resources, and DNS.
- 📜 **Log-based alerting** — Promtail scrapes container logs and Loki fires alerts whenever `ERROR` appears in any microservice or the Angular frontend.
- 📊 **Kube-Prometheus-Stack** — out-of-the-box dashboards, alert rules, and metric scraping for the entire cluster.
- 📈 **Dual autoscaling** — Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) for pods and Cluster Autoscaler for nodes (min: 0, desired: 1, max: 3).
- 🌐 **NGINX Ingress + NLB** — public internet access via a Network Load Balancer, with path rewrites, rate limiting, and client-side routing support for the Angular SPA.
- 🗄️ **Persistent PostgreSQL** — StatefulSet backed by Amazon EFS via the EFS CSI driver, survives pod restarts and node replacements.
- 🤖 **AI-enriched alerts** — the alert-analyzer pod receives Prometheus Alertmanager webhooks, fetches the surrounding logs from Loki, and asks OpenAI GPT-4o-mini to diagnose the problem before forwarding the analysis via AWS SNS.
- 📨 **AWS SNS delivery** — enriched alert emails delivered to any confirmed subscriber.
- 🦊 **GitLab CE pipeline** — self-hosted GitLab CE on EC2, with a GitLab Agent (agentk) and GitLab Runner deployed directly into the EKS cluster for in-cluster builds and deployments.
- 💥 **Full teardown** — a second Ansible playbook removes every Kubernetes resource, Helm release, CloudFormation stack, IAM role, and SNS subscription cleanly.

##🧱 Architecture

### Application (default namespace)

| Workload | Description |
|---|---|
| `webapp` | Angular SPA served by NGINX |
| `owner-service` | Spring Boot microservice — dog owner management (port 8081) |
| `user-service` | Spring Boot microservice — user/staff management (port 8082) |
| `org-service` | Spring Boot microservice — organization management (port 8083) |
| `postgres` | PostgreSQL 16 StatefulSet, persisted to EFS (10 Gi) |

The Angular frontend routes API calls through the Ingress:
- `/api/owner/**` → rewrites to `/owner/**` on `owner-service`
- `/api/user/**` → rewrites to `/user/**` on `user-service`
- `/api/org/**` → rewrites to `/organization/**` on `org-service`
- All other paths → served by `webapp` (SPA fallback to `index.html`)

### Monitoring (monitoring namespace)

| Workload | Description |
|---|---|
| Kube-Prometheus-Stack | Prometheus scraper, Alertmanager, Prometheus Gateway, Grafana |
| Loki (monolithic) | Log aggregation and alert rule evaluation |
| Promtail | DaemonSet co-located with the application node; scrapes container logs |
| alert-analyzer | Custom Flask/Gunicorn pod — receives Alertmanager webhooks, queries Loki, enriches alerts with OpenAI, publishes to SNS |

**Alert flow:**
1. A log line matching `ERROR` appears in any microservice or the frontend.
2. Loki evaluates the alert rule (5-minute window) and fires after 1 minute of sustained matches.
3. Alertmanager forwards the webhook to `alert-analyzer`.
4. `alert-analyzer` queries Loki for the surrounding log context (±3 minutes, up to 70 lines).
5. GPT-4o-mini analyzes the alert name, severity, pod, and logs.
6. The AI response is published to the SNS topic `doggy-alerts` and delivered by email.

### GitLab (gitlab namespace)

| Component | Description |
|---|---|
| GitLab CE | Self-hosted on the management EC2 instance, fronted by an ALB |
| doggy-agent (agentk) | GitLab Kubernetes Agent — connects the cluster to GitLab |
| gitlab-runner | Helm-installed runner in the cluster; builds and deploys via ECR and `kubectl` |

GitLab projects created automatically:
- `doggyapp/frontend`
- `doggyapp/owner-service`
- `doggyapp/user-service`
- `doggyapp/org-service`
- `doggyapp/pipeline-config` (holds the agent configuration)

### System (kube-system namespace)

| Workload | Description |
|---|---|
| Cluster Autoscaler | Scales nodes between 0 and 3; uses IRSA for EC2 Auto Scaling permissions |
| EFS CSI Driver (addon) | Provides the `efs-sc` StorageClass for PostgreSQL persistent storage |

### AWS Infrastructure (CloudFormation stacks)

| Stack | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `doggy-stack` | Base VPC, EKS cluster, node groups, EFS filesystem, GitLab ALB (deployed from CloudFormationArchitecture) |
| `cluster-autoscaler-iam-role` | IRSA role for the Cluster Autoscaler |
| `efs-csi-driver-iam-role` | IRSA role for the EFS CSI driver addon |
| `alert-hook-iam-role` | IRSA role granting the alert-analyzer pod access to Secrets Manager and SNS |
| `gitlab-runner-iam-role` | IRSA role granting the GitLab Runner access to ECR and EKS |
| `sns-doggy` | SNS topic `doggy-alerts` and email subscription |
| `doggy-dns-tls` | Route 53 A record aliasing `doggyapp.click` to the NLB |

