##🚀 Deployment

    Ensure you have the doggy EKS stack deployed from here https://github.com/DoggyApp/CloudFormationArchitecture.git to region us-east-1. Ensure that you have a user with all the necessary priviledges created in AWS IAM Identity Center. 

        # go to your EC2 page in AWS and find the mgmt instance you just deployed, make sure it is running and then note the instance ID. (You might want to wait 20 min, the start up script installs Python10, which is needed to run the latest version of ansible, this takes a long while, so even if you log into the session once the instance appears it will still take a good while longer to spin up the environment. A good way to check that it is done is to wait for an email from AWS SNS with a confirmation to subscribe to "doggy-alerts" this is after the heavy lifting in the script). 
        # from your terminal run, 

        aws ssm start-session --target <your-instance-id>

        # this will start a remote session in that EC2 instance. 

        # you can also SSM directly into the instance from the AWS console, the above is just my prefered method, and it will be helpful later on to have done it this way if you want to view the full functionality of the environment. 

        # in the start up script for this instance we set the .bashrc file to acces the py-10 virtual environment log in with 

        sudo su - ec2-user 

        # you will be prompted to login to your user in IAM Identity Center. This can be configured with multifactor autherntication and to time out making it more secure than access keys which can be stolen. 
        
        # and  make sure that this is your tag in the command line is "(py10-ansible-env) [ec2-user@ip-10-98-25-84 ~]$" 
        # we also git cloned this very project into the instance under /home/ec-user, make sure that it is there

        cd kubernetesArchitecture 

        # on the first start up you will need to set your current user into RBAC this can be done with the preregistered command...

        setadmin 

        # next you will set up the gitlab pipeline with the pregegistered command... 

        setupgit 

        # finally you will set up the monitoring suit with the preregistered command 

        setupkube

        # The start up script should have automatically deployed the environment, 
        # Confirm that the script ran completely it will produce a file called environment-info.txt with values for the gitlab ALB, temp password for GitLab, DNS name for the  application, ect. 
        # visit the gitlab alb in the browser, log in and create the webhooks between the pipeline and your local repository (it should be as simple as creating an API Key and using the command 
        # git remote --add -push origin https://<APIkey>@<URL> or something close to that.) Push to deploy the pipeline. 

        # confirm that the project is running 

        kubectl get pods 

        # you should see the microservices and frontend pods, as well as the postgres pod. 

        kubectl get pods -n monitoring 

        # you should see the "prometheus" "grafana" "loki" and "alert-analyzer". 

        kubectl get pods -n kube-system 

        # you should see "cluster-autoscaler" 

        # The below command will give you the URL to the web page so you can confirm that it is there and that the notification systems are running 

        kubectl get ingress 

        # copy the URL into your browser, it should be "doggyapp.click" as this is the purchased domain that I am using. 

        # you can also test that the client side routing is working by typing in the browser "https://doggy-app.click/dev-server" dev-server being a common url that bots scraping the internet will attempt to access sensitive files, it should lead to a "/not-found" page.
        
        # Ensure that Grafana is running 
        # This is the command to get the password to log into the UI (it should be "prom-operator")

        kubectl get secret -n monitoring kube-prometheus-stack-grafana -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 --decode

        # Grafana is running in the cluster so you have to port forward to reach it from the bastion 

        kubectl port-forward -n monitoring svc/kube-prometheus-stack-grafana 3000:80

        # the bastion doesn't have a browser and Grafana is viewed in the browser so you have to port forward again from the bastion to your local computer, you can do this with Session Manager. Open a new terminal window on your local computer and enter this command. 

        aws ssm start-session --target <your-instance-id> --document-name AWS-StartPortForwardingSession --parameters '{"portNumber":["3000"],"localPortNumber":["3000"]}'

        # go to your browser and type in http://localhost:3000 grafana will appear there, log in with the default user name "admin" and the password that you collected 3 commands ago. 

        # Once logged in you can explore and see dashboards, alert rules, logs and data sources. 

        # When you're ready to take down the application you can delete it by using the alias command that should have been set in the bashrc. file... 

        teardown 

This alias runs `teardown.yaml`, which:
- Deletes the Ingress and waits for the AWS NLB to be fully deprovisioned before proceeding.
- Uninstalls all Helm releases (Promtail, Loki, Prometheus, Cluster Autoscaler, GitLab Agent, GitLab Runner).
- Deletes the `monitoring`, `gitlab`, and `ingress-nginx` namespaces.
- Deletes all CloudFormation stacks (autoscaler IAM role, EFS CSI role, alert hook role, GitLab runner role, SNS topic, DNS/TLS stack).
- Unsubscribes all confirmed SNS subscriptions before deleting the topic.
- Removes GitLab secrets from Secrets Manager.
- Deletes all images from Elastic Container Registry 

        # go to CloudFormation in the AWS console and delete the doggy-stack from the base stack. And it will clear all traces of the application from your AWS, inclusing subsciptions to SNS topics. 

##🛠️ Troubleshooting 

    In the bashrc. is a functions to access the ansible setup script for the appplication. The command is... "setup". If the application is not running you can run this script indepotently and read the error logs. I have attached the -vvv flag which makes them verbose. 

    also, if you cat \vars\log\user-data.log you will find a file with the output from the start up script. This will likely direct you to the problem. 

##🛡️ Security 

- 🔐 NGINX runs with `shell: /sbin/nologin` — the process cannot spawn a shell.
- 🔐 NGINX Ingress terminates TLS at the controller; traffic inside the cluster is unencrypted.
- 🔐 NGINX files and directories are owned by `root`.
- 🔐 Ingress rate limits: 5 concurrent connections, 120 requests per minute, burst multiplier of 3.
- 🔐 Client-side routing returns `/not-found` for unrecognised paths (e.g. `/dev-server`, `/wp-admin`), preventing accidental information disclosure to scanners.
- 🔐 Grafana is not exposed through the Ingress. It is only reachable via `kubectl port-forward` inside an authenticated SSM session.
- 🔐 Secrets (OpenAI key, PostgreSQL password, GitLab tokens) are stored in AWS Secrets Manager and injected at runtime via IRSA — no secrets are baked into container images or Kubernetes manifests.
- 🔐 All IAM roles use IRSA (IAM Roles for Service Accounts) with scoped trust policies. No node-level IAM permissions are used.
- 🔐 Application images use minimal base images (distroless/slim variants) pinned to `latest` to pull the most recent security patches.
- ⚠️ **Known gap:** Kubernetes network policies are not yet configured. Pods in the `default` namespace can reach services in `monitoring` via cluster DNS. DNS restrictions or `NetworkPolicy` resources should be added to prevent publicly accessible pods from making arbitrary in-cluster API calls.

